15 WHEREAS, the America After 3PM survey indicates that approximately 18 percent of
16 Georgia's school-aged youth are in after-school programs, but over 600,000 more of
17 Georgia's youth would participate in an afterschool program if one was available in their
18 community; and
19 WHEREAS, Georgia is committed to preparing our youth for the jobs of tomorrow, and
20 after-school programs provide opportunities for college readiness; career exploration,
21 especially in the areas of science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM); and expanded
22 learning opportunities that help youth gain hands-on experience and foster skills including
23 communication, teamwork, and consensus building; and
24 WHEREAS, the Georgia Department of Education partnered with the Georgia Statewide
25 Afterschool Network to establish the Building Opportunities in Out-of-School Time
26 (BOOST) grants program to distribute approximately $85 million to afterschool and summer
27 learning programs utilizing evidence-based practices and whole child supports; and
28 WHEREAS, the BOOST grants program supported organizations operating in 115 Georgia
29 counties that served 86,386 young people during the 2023-24 academic year and 82,827
30 young people during the summer of 2024; and
31 WHEREAS, there are many public and private entities providing quality programming, such
32 as 21st Century Community Learning Centers, Division of Family and Children Services Out
33 of School Services program, Department of Behavioral Health and Developmental
34 Disabilities Prevention Clubhouses, 4-H, YMCAs, and Boys and Girls Clubs; and
35 WHEREAS, the Georgia Statewide Afterschool Network, a public-private collaborative, has
36 convened these organizations and after school providers from across the state for the sixth
